\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\ulnone\fs28 Q1. What is a cloud technology? Discuss some of its key features.\par
Ans. \b0 Cloud computing is on-demand access, via the internet, to computing resources\f1\emdash applications, servers (physical servers and virtual servers), data storage, development tools, networking capabilities, and more\emdash hosted at a remote data center managed by a cloud services provider (or CSP). The CSP makes these resources available for a monthly subscription fee or bills them according to usage.\f0\lang1033  Some of its key features are as follows:-\par
1. Resource pooling and elasticity\par
In cloud computing, resources are pooled to serve a large number of customers. Cloud computing uses multi-tenancy where different resources are dynamically allocated and de-allocated according to demand. From the user\rquote s end, it is not possible to know where the resource actually resides.\par
2. Self-service and On-demand service\par
Cloud computing is based on self-service and on-demand service models. It should allow the user to interact with the cloud to perform tasks like building, deploying, managing, and scheduling. The user should be able to access computing capabilities as and when they are needed and without any interaction from the cloud-service provider.\par
3. Pricing\par
Cloud computing does not have any upfront cost. It is completely based on usage. The user is billed based on the amount of resources they use. This helps the user to track their usage and ultimately help to reduce cost. Cloud computing must provide means to capture, monitor, and control usage information for accurate billing.\par
4. Quality of Service\par
Cloud computing must assure the best service level for users. Services outlined in the service-level agreements must include guarantees on round-the-clock availability, adequate resources, performance, and bandwidth. Any compromise on these guarantees could prove fatal for customers.\par
5. Security\par
Data security is one of the best features of cloud computing. Cloud services make a copy of the stored data to prevent any kind of data loss. If one server loses data by any chance, the copied version is restored from the other server. This feature comes in handy when multiple users are working on a particular file in real-time, and one file suddenly gets corrupted.\par
