Q6. What are the drivers of cloud computing? Discuss.\par
Ans. \b0 The key drivers behind the mass-migration to cloud computing are as follows:-\par
1. Cost Saving- When you move to cloud-based computing, you are utilizing the infrastructure of the cloud provider rather than your own infrastructure. This means that the cost of maintenance, updating equipment, and managing software on the devices becomes the responsibility of the service provider.\par
\par
2. Convenience- Businesses are increasingly becoming more mobile as technology enables them to do so. Of course, employees still have to be able to access and share files when they are working outside of the office. With cloud-based storage, users can easily access the files they need wherever they are located. This enables your employees to focus on the tasks that can actually drive growth in your business like meeting face-to-face with clients or prospecting for new business.\par
3. Security- It\rquote s hard not to turn on the daily news and see a story about the latest major data breach. While cloud-based computing isn\rquote t 100 percent secure, your business does get the benefit of regular security updates. Most importantly, the cost and management of the new security doesn\rquote t fall in your lap. Many cloud providers are also implementing artificial intelligence to help identify and track down the latest threats to provide even greater security.\par
4. Recovery- A fire or flood in your business could be devastating if you store data on-premise. Not only do you need to recover data, you may need to replace infrastructure at a very high cost. This can lead to prolonged downtime, increased expenses, and lost revenue. With cloud-based computing and cloud-based storage, a disaster in your business doesn\rquote t mean you have to go completely dark. \par
5. Efficiency- With advanced capture and cloud storage, documents can instantly be analyzed and stored in a way that makes it easy for your business to access and review documents. This can be incredibly handy if you are in the process of going through an audit.\par
\b Q7. What are Hybrid Clouds? Discuss its benefits and limitations.\par
Ans.\b0  A hybrid cloud is one in which applications are running in a combination of different environments. Hybrid cloud computing approaches are widespread because almost no one today relies entirely on the public cloud. Many of you have invested millions of dollars and thousands of hours into on-premises infrastructure over the past few decades. Benefits of Hybrid cloud are:-\par
1. Effective application governance- A hybrid approach allows you to decide where your application sits and where hybrid computing happens. This can help improve privacy and ensure compliance for your regulated applications.\par
2. Improved performance and reduced latency- Sometimes, distributed apps at remote locations benefit from a hybrid cloud solution. For applications with low latency requirements, hybrid computing happens close to the end users.\par
3. Flexible operations- Hybrid computing gives you the flexibility to operate in the environment that\rquote s best for you. For example, by building with containers, you can create portable applications and easily move between public and private clouds.\par
On the other hand, there are some limitations of the hybrid cloud:-\par
1. Difficult to Implement- A hybrid cloud environment can be difficult to implement and maintain. Design and implementation often require the skills of an experienced cloud architect to ensure that the public cloud implementation being used is compatible with private infrastructure. \par
2. Visibility- The combination of disparate environments in the hybrid cloud model creates a need for full visibility across the entire environment. IT admin must be able to monitor systems, applications, and processes in all environments. This can be difficult if using multiple cloud providers with different proprietary management tools.\par
3. Compatibility and Data Integration- Applications and files used in a hybrid cloud environment must be compatible with all environments, whether on-prem or the private or public cloud. Incompatibilities can negate the benefit of being able to share resources and workloads between environments.\b\par
